Here is a simple C++ program that calculates the nth Fibonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

// Recursive function to calculate nth Fibonacci number
int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 1)
        return n;
    else
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter a positive integer: ";
    cin >> n;

    if(n < 0) {
        cout << "Invalid input! Please enter a non-negative integer." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << fibonacci(n) << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, `fibonacci` is a recursive function that calculates the nth Fibonacci number. It checks if `n` is less than or equal to 1, in which case it returns `n` (since the 0th and 1st Fibonacci numbers are 0 and 1, respectively). Otherwise, it recursively calls itself for `n-1` and `n-2`, and returns the sum of these two calls.

The `main` function prompts the user to input a positive integer, checks if the input is valid, and then prints the nth Fibonacci number using the `fibonacci` function.

Please note that this recursive solution has exponential time complexity due to repeated calculations for the same Fibonacci numbers. For larger inputs, consider using dynamic programming or matrix exponentiation for better performance.

Here is a C++ program that calculates the nth number in the sequence where each number is the sum of the three preceding ones, starting with 0, -1, and -1:

```cpp
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

// Function to calculate nth number in the given sequence
int sequence(int n) {
    if (n == 0)
        return 0;
    else if (n == 1 || n == 2)
        return -1;
    else {
        int prev3 = 0, prev2 = -1, prev1 = -1;

        for (int i = 3; i <= n; i++) {
            int current = prev1 + prev2 + prev3;
            prev3 = prev2;
            prev2 = prev1;
            prev1 = current;
        }

        return prev1;
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter a positive integer: ";
    cin >> n;

    if(n < 0) {
        cout << "Invalid input! Please enter a non-negative integer." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "The " << n << "th number in the sequence is: " << sequence(n) << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, the `sequence` function calculates the nth number in the sequence. It handles the base cases where n is 0, 1, or 2, returning 0, -1, and -1 respectively. For larger n, it initializes three variables `prev3`, `prev2`, and `prev1` to represent the last three numbers in the sequence.

The function then enters a loop, starting from i = 3 and iterating up to n. In each iteration, it calculates the current number as the sum of the three preceding numbers (`prev1`, `prev2`, and `prev3`), updates these variables to keep track of the last three numbers, and returns the value of `prev1` after the loop ends.

The `main` function prompts the user to input a positive integer, checks if the input is valid, and then prints the nth number in the sequence using the `sequence` function.

Here is a simple HTML page with embedded JavaScript to display a random joke from an array of 4 jokes when a button is clicked:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Joke Generator</title>
    <style>
        #joke-box {
            width: 300px;
            padding: 20px;
            margin: 20px auto;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Random Joke Generator</h1>
    <button id="get-joke">Get a Joke</button>
    <div id="joke-box"></div>

    <script>
        const jokes = [
            "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything!",
            "What do you call fake spaghetti? An impasta.",
            "Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field!",
            "Why did the bicycle fall over? Because it was two-tired."
        ];

        document.getElementById('get-joke').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
            const joke = jokes[randomIndex];
            document.getElementById('joke-box').innerText = joke;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, I've added a bit of CSS to style the joke box for better readability. When the user clicks the "Get a Joke" button, the JavaScript code will select a random joke from the `jokes` array and display it in the `#joke-box` div.

